        <p>The heat map displays debt-to-GDP ratios that exceed 100 by using a gradient scale from blue (lower) to red (higher). This approach follows recommendations from Datawrapper’s “What to Consider When Choosing Colors for Data Visualization,” as utilizing two hues for a gradient can make a map more decipherable. The “Value” scale to the right of the chart further indicates this shift. However, a weakness is that the value scale does not immediately provide the viewer with clear information regarding where the highest ratios over 100 begin. While the shift in colors suggests this, it requires further analysis of the heat map itself and isn’t very useful for quickly identifying specific amounts or ranges.</p>
    </div>

